set();\n        }\n    }\n\n    private static Class<?> invokeGeneratedClassLookup(String className) throws Throwable {\n        ClassLoader classLoader = RequestSpecificationImplInner_assertCorrectNumberOfPathParams_closure18Test.class\n                .getClassLoader();\n        Class<?> closureClass = classLoader.loadClass(CLOSURE_CLASS_NAME);\n        Method classHelper = closureClass.getDeclaredMethod(\"class$\", String.class);\n        classHelper.setAccessible(true);\n        return (Class<?>) classHelper.invoke(null, className);\n    }\n}\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1781029141751}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing coverage report issues**\n\nI’m looking into a coverage report that shows none for a class, which might stem from the direct method not being counted since it's handled by LambdaMetafactory. Is it possible that Class.forName should ensure it's counted? \n\nThe user mentioned a previous dynamic-access report might have included attempts. I’m considering if the class$ helper exists in the source but not in the runtime jar, and if the line number may differ. Could lambda optimization be affecting visibility? I'll need to explore usable public APIs in Groovy that lead to CallSiteArray creation.\n\n**Examining Class.forName behavior**\n\nI’m wondering if the coverage report requires the \"java.lang.Class#forName <- class$\" to be explicitly tested. Since the `className` is the same and may not trigger metadata creation if the class is already loaded, I should consider whether a dynamic agent records calls independently. \n\nWhat if passing a different class name could help? The metadata might filter out library packages if the target class name is the same. I think Graal's tracing agent might still record Class.forName, even for already loaded classes, but perhaps the package-private status of class$ is influencing this. I’ll have to check the stack for library-only content.\n\n**Exploring Groovy invocation options**\n\nI'm considering whether I can generate a helper through the Groovy runtime MOP since `ObjectMapperSerializationContextImpl` implements GroovyObject. I might use `InvokerHelper.invokeStaticMethod(ObjectMapperSerializationContextImpl.class, \"class$\", CONTEXT_CLASS_NAME` to leverage Groovy dispatch. However, this might rely on reflection rather than direct testing. \n\nI wonder if GroovyShell could help, but dynamic class loading isn't ideal. It seems like I'd have to bend the rules since tests are confined to the Java under src/test/java.