citly tested. Since the `className` is the same and may not trigger metadata creation if the class is already loaded, I should consider whether a dynamic agent records calls independently. \\n\\nWhat if passing a different class name could help? The metadata might filter out library packages if the target class name is the same. I think Graal's tracing agent might still record Class.forName, even for already loaded classes, but perhaps the package-private status of class$ is influencing this. I’ll have to check the stack for library-only content.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Groovy invocation options**\\n\\nI'm considering whether I can generate a helper through the Groovy runtime MOP since `ObjectMapperSerializationContextImpl` implements GroovyObject. I might use `InvokerHelper.invokeStaticMethod(ObjectMapperSerializationContextImpl.class, \\\"class$\\\", CONTEXT_CLASS_NAME` to leverage Groovy dispatch. However, this might rely on reflection rather than direct testing. \\n\\nI wonder if GroovyShell could help, but dynamic class loading isn't ideal. It seems like I'd have to bend the rules since tests are confined to the Java under src/test/java. Maybe I can add a test in Groovy after all.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting generated tests**\\n\\nIt seems like I need to add or refine tests to cover remaining cases. I should take a closer look at the other generated class tests to see if they're using `classloader.loadClass` directly instead of using method handles. It's important to ensure I understand their approach to see if that could improve my own tests. Let’s figure out what adjustments I might need to make to enhance test coverage effectively!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_BVE0OnCrDSYhEkT4DyFrla8K|fc_00f22cce1660d92e016a285913599081978c7c1657f580146d", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io_rest_assured/rest_assured/RequestSpecificationImplInne